By the way, the isolation of penicillin from fungi was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, he, being cold, sowed mucus from his own nose on a Petri dish (this is a glass lid in which experiments with bacteria are carried out) and a few days later found that the bacteria were destroyed.
Almost as by accident they were discovered and penicillin.
Fleming's name was included in the list of 100 most outstanding personalities in the history of mankind.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the oldest diseases previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel prize, in 1945, Fleming arrived in the French capital, the Paris Newspapers wrote: "For the defeat of fascism and the liberation of France, he did more than dozens of divisions."
Experts estimate that Fleming's discovery of the world's first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million people on Earth.
Alexander Fleming died of a heart attack at his home in London in 1955.
He was cremated, and a week later his ashes were buried in the famous London Cathedral of St. Paul.
Where, by the way, my wife and I paid attention to this talkative Russian-speaking guide.
And a few years later the statue of Alexander Fleming in full growth we had a chance to observe in the most unexpected place in the capital of Spain.
