There is no word for pressure.
Right - to cling to.
The word "press" in the sense of "to weigh, to influence, to influence" exists only phonetically, because we hear the sound [a] instead of [o] in the word "to dominate".
We use this word, believing that it comes from the word "pressure".
But "pressure" and "dominate" etymologically are not only not close, but even in some sense opposite.
See for yourself.
To dominate (Church.-bookish, outdated) - means "enough, full, enough, to be sufficient for someone or something to satisfy."
To be content, pleasure - related words.
Previously, it still had the meaning of "do not depend on anything, have a self-sufficient value" - "to dominate yourself."
Old Church Slavonic "doville" related words "command" and "will".
Press, suppress - completely different.
These words are really frightening "relatives": daos - "wolf" (crushing sheep), deyja - "die" and dvaid - "oppress".
The similar phonetic appearance of the words "pressure" and "dominate", as well as the inevitable obsolescence of the latter, forced them to enter into contamination.
So we have this very "d[a]vlet", which is used in writing through "a", which, in a good way, wrong and impossible in terms of the processes of occurrence and development of these words.
So, the right - to cling to.
But this word is outdated, in its correct meaning is no longer used.
If you want to note that any circumstances/people have a negative impact on you from above, use the word "push".
You can also use the "apply pressure" design, but remember that this is a stationery.
